  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concern—it's a lived reality for many who've struggled with the idea that they might not belong in these fields. As someone who grew up in a family where my father only attended primary school but my mother had a bachelor's degree, I've seen firsthand how expectations can shape opportunities. When I was a teenager, I remember sitting in math class, feeling that the numbers were just too big for me, and wondering if I was just not cut out for it. That kind of self-doubt isn't something that disappears with age—it lingers, especially when you're surrounded by people who seem to know more than you do. In my work as a carpenter, I've seen how stereotypes about who can succeed in technical fields can hold people back, even when they have the skills and dedication. I think addressing stereotype threat in STEM requires more than just changing the curriculum; it's about creating an environment where everyone feels valued and supported. It's about recognizing that when someone feels like they don't belong, their performance suffers, and that's a real problem. We need to start early, in schools, by teaching kids that their worth isn't tied to their gender or background. It's also important to have mentors who understand these challenges and can guide students through them. For me, as someone who's lived through this myself, it's clear that addressing stereotype threat isn't just about fixing a problem—it's about building a future where everyone has the chance to thrive.",
